# AI Declaration

## Tool Used
Microsoft Copilot

## How It Was Used
- Generating boilerplate code structure for each module
- Writing initial implementations of the crawler, indexer, and search functions
- Suggesting test cases and helping write the test suite
- Debugging errors during development
- Understanding libraries such as requests and BeautifulSoup
- Helping implement TF-IDF ranking after I identified that raw word count was insufficient

## Critical Evaluation
Copilot was useful for getting things written quickly, but it made mistakes that required my own understanding to catch.

The clearest example was a file path bug — it saved the index to `src/data/index.json` but the load command expected it at `data/index.json`. All tests passed because they mock the file system, so the bug was invisible until I ran the tool manually. I had to trace the path logic myself to find and fix it.

It also initially ranked search results by raw word count. Having studied the module lectures on query processing, I recognised this was a weak approach and directed Copilot to implement TF-IDF ranking instead. The code it produced was correct, but knowing what to ask for required understanding the material first.

Overall, Copilot sped up development but did not replace understanding, it depended on it.

